            <fr:title text="Frame of opens of a general scheme">Frame of opens of a general scheme</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For a <fr:link href="/schm-86OJ/" title="Scheme" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-86OJ/" display-uri="schm-86OJ" type="local">scheme</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, there is a bijective correspondence between its frame of opens and <fr:link href="/schm-TCWT/" title="Quasi-coherent ideal" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-TCWT/" display-uri="schm-TCWT" type="local">quasi-coherent ideals</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Idl}_Q(X)]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    Again we prove a dual equivalence between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Idl}_Q(X)]]></fr:tex> and closed subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. For any (quasi-coherent) ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{X}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:link href="/schm-5KCL/" title="Sheaf of ideals generate quasi-closed immersions" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-5KCL/" display-uri="schm-5KCL" type="local">Construction <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-5KCL/" display-uri="schm-5KCL" /></fr:link> gives us a closed subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_{\mathcal {I}}]]></fr:tex> already. Now for a closed subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, we construct an ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}_Y]]></fr:tex> such that for any open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>,
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathcal {I}_Y(U) := \{a\in \mathcal {O}_{X}(U)\mid \forall  y \in  Y \cap  U.\  y \not \models  a\}.  ]]></fr:tex>
    This ideal is quasi-coherent, because if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> is affine open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex>, then the intersection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y \cap  \operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex>, in the notation of <fr:link href="/idem-comm-HLDT/" title="Frame of opens of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" /></fr:link>, is the closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> for some ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>, 
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathcal {I}_{Y}(\operatorname {Spec} A/a) = \{b\in  A/a\mid \forall  y \in  C_I.\  y \not \models  b\} = a \wedge  I. ]]></fr:tex>
    By <fr:link href="/schm-2CQ4/" title="Local criteria for quasi-coherent ideals" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-2CQ4/" display-uri="schm-2CQ4" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-2CQ4/" display-uri="schm-2CQ4" /></fr:link> this means <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}_Y]]></fr:tex> is quasi-coherent.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    If we now start from a closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ 
      \begin {align*}
        x\in  C_{\mathcal {I}_Y} 
        &\Leftrightarrow  1 \not \in  \mathcal {I}_{Y,x} \\ 
        &\Leftrightarrow  \forall  U\text {open}\ni  x.\, 1 \not \in  \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \\ 
        &\Leftrightarrow  \forall  U\text {open}\ni  x.\, Y \cap  U \neq  \emptyset  \\ 
        &\Leftrightarrow  x \in  Y
      \end {align*}
    ]]></fr:tex>
    The third equivalence holds since by construction, 
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ 1 \in  \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \Leftrightarrow  \forall  y \in  Y \cap  U.\  y \not \models  1 \Leftrightarrow  Y \cap  U = \emptyset . ]]></fr:tex>
    The final equivalence holds since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is closed.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    Now if we start from a quasi-coherent ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}]]></fr:tex>, to show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I} = \mathcal {I}_{C_{\mathcal {I}}}]]></fr:tex>, it suffices to show this on an affine open cover. For any affine open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_{\mathcal {I}} \cap  \operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex> is closed in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex>, it corresponds to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> for an ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}]]></fr:tex> is quasi-coherent, we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}(\operatorname {Spec} A) = \widetilde {I}]]></fr:tex>. Hence,
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathcal {I}_{C_{\mathcal {I}}}(\operatorname {Spec} A) = \{a \in  A\mid \forall  y \in  C_{\mathcal {I}} \cap  \operatorname {Spec} A.\  y \not \models  a\} = I = \mathcal {I}(\operatorname {Spec} A). ]]></fr:tex>
    This shows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {I}_{C_{\mathcal {I}}} = \mathcal {I}]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
